also always found it both fascinating and perplexing, and maybe even a litt=
le familiar. As loyal readers know well, I started my career at the beginni=
ng of the end of the magazine era=E2=80=94back in a time and place called M=
idtown in the early aughts. In those days, we were convinced that the cultu=
ral product we churned out every month was immune to changing tastes and te=
chnologies, and we were superbly confident that consumers valued our work m=
ore than the sort of garbage accumulating on nascent social media platforms=
=2E Alas, in many ways, the humbling=
 that the industry endured=E2=80=94reverb=
erations that have since defined my career=E2=80=94presaged similar disloca=
tions across the economy: the music business, the television industry, and =
yes, even the beauty trade. These days, the legacy cosmetics giants are als=
o watching their moats evaporate in real time as they race to keep up with =
the whims of younger generations: both what they want to consume and their =
point of purchase. Few entities
embody this generational transition more than Est=C3=A9e Lauder Companies, =
the family-controlled dynasty that helped forge the industry as we know it,=
 and has endured its own very public humbling in recent times as the stock =
has fallen 75 percent in the last three years.

On Monday, Rachel reported that Lauder=E2=80=99s C.E.O. Fabrizio Freda was =
announcing his retirement ahead of the company=E2=80=99s earnings call=E2=
=80=94a sure sign that the family and the board wanted to communicate to th=
e markets that they were focused on a turnaround. Of course, this followed =
the recent departure of the company=E2=80=99s well-regarded C.F.O. Tracey T=
ravis, who sits on the board of both Accenture and Meta. There was more: Ra=
chel suggested that other executives would be departing, too.

Freda isn=E2=80=99t going anywhere immediately. He=E2=80=99ll stay on until=
 next June, the end of the 2025 fiscal year. Naturally, however, the news h=
as set this cinematic universe ablaze. Will the Lauders elevate
one of their own, chief data officer Jane Lauder, into the perch? Amid a se=
ason of uncharacteristically high succession intrigue=E2=80=94at LVMH, JPMo=
rgan Chase, Disney, and even the White House=E2=80=94the sitch at ELC may y=
et be the most compelling. I behoove you to turn your attention to Rachel=
=E2=80=99s fabulously good piece, The Est=C3=A9e Exodus ( https://puck.news=
/the-estee-lauder-exodus/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%288%2=
F24%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%287%2F19%2F24%29&utm=
_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd1=
2a ), to fully comprehend the familial, political, and economic dynamics.

But if you only have time for one late summer weekend read, I=E2=80=99d tur=
n your attention to another double-barreled piece regarding another sort of=
 succession. Right after Rachel filed her story on Freda, my partner John O=
urand emailed me a copy of Edgar Bronfman Jr.=E2=80=99s pitch deck to inves=
tors to acquire Paramount Global from
another scion, Shari Redstone.

Yes, yes, I know that the sprawling, certifiably endless Paramount auction =
has been an infatuation here at Puck=E2=80=94some bankers have joked, half =
seriously, that we should collect a deal fee on the transaction from all ou=
r perspicacious reporting=E2=80=94but now John has unveiled the latest twis=
t. Bronfman=E2=80=99s pitch deck not only crystallizes his strategy for the=
 company, but also the management team he=E2=80=99d deploy into Times Squar=
e to fix the business. Bronfman=E2=80=99s Closing Pitch ( https://puck.news=
/edgar-bronfmans-closing-pitch-for-paramount/?utm_campaign=3DThe+Backstory+=
-+SUBSCRIBERS+%288%2F24%2F24%29&utm_content=3DThe+Backstory+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%=
287%2F19%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_ter=
m=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ) eloquently builds on the previous reportage from M=
att Belloni and Bill Cohan and yet crystallizes it in a new light. After al=
l, this is one of the great sagas of our time,
and precisely what you should expect from Puck.

Have a great weekend,
Jon

