          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Early Monday mornin=
g, shortly before I was about to load the Radio Flyer to take the kids to t=
he beach, <b>Rachel Strugatz </b>dropped a note into Puck=E2=80=99s now-fam=
ous Slack channel that I instantaneously knew was going to change the cours=
e of the day, and maybe even the complexion of the week.<br/><br/>Rachel, o=
f course, is the most connected and acerbic reporter at work today focused =
on the six-hundred-ish billion-dollar beauty industry=E2=80=94from the publ=
icly traded behemoths, like L=E2=80=99Or=C3=A9al, to the new era of influen=
cer-led insurgents, like <b>Selena Gomez</b>=E2=80=99s Rare Beauty. And jus=
t like Hollywood or the media or Washington, the beauty industry offers its=
 own veritable cinematic universe that=E2=80=99s filled with strivers and i=
ncumbents, hucksters and hegemons. It=E2=80=99s exactly the sort of ecosyst=
em that we love to unfurl here at Puck. <br/><br/>I=E2=80=99ve
also always found it both fascinating and perplexing, and maybe even a litt=
le familiar. As loyal readers know well, I started my career at the beginni=
ng of the end of the magazine era=E2=80=94back in a time and place called M=
idtown in the early aughts. In those days, we were convinced that the cultu=
ral product we churned out every month was immune to changing tastes and te=
chnologies, and we were superbly confident that consumers valued our work m=
ore than the sort of garbage accumulating on nascent social media platforms=
=2E Alas, in many ways, the humbling=
 that the industry endured=E2=80=94reverb=
erations that have since defined my career=E2=80=94presaged similar disloca=
tions across the economy: the music business, the television industry, and =
yes, even the beauty trade. These days, the legacy cosmetics giants are als=
o watching their moats evaporate in real time as they race to keep up with =
the whims of younger generations: both what they want to consume and their =
point of purchase. Few entities
embody this generational transition more than Est=C3=A9e Lauder Companies, =
the family-controlled dynasty that helped forge the industry as we know it,=
 and has endured its own very public humbling in recent times as the stock =
has fallen 75 percent in the last three years.<br/><br/>On Monday, Rachel r=
eported that Lauder=E2=80=99s C.E.O. <b>Fabrizio Freda </b>was announcing h=
is retirement ahead of the company=E2=80=99s earnings call=E2=80=94a sure s=
ign that the family and the board wanted to communicate to the markets that=
 they were focused on a turnaround. Of course, this followed the recent dep=
arture of the company=E2=80=99s well-regarded C.F.O. <b>Tracey Travis</b>, =
who sits on the board of both Accenture and Meta. There was more: Rachel su=
ggested that other executives would be departing, too. <br/><br/>Freda isn=
=E2=80=99t going anywhere immediately. He=E2=80=99ll stay on until next Jun=
e, the end of the 2025 fiscal year. Naturally, however, the news has set th=
is cinematic universe ablaze. Will the Lauders elevate
one of their own, chief data officer <b>Jane Lauder</b>, into the perch? Am=
id a season of uncharacteristically high succession intrigue=E2=80=94at LVM=
H, JPMorgan Chase, Disney, and even the White House=E2=80=94the sitch at EL=
C may yet be the most compelling. I behoove you to turn your attention to R=
achel=E2=80=99s fabulously good piece, <i><u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.=
news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1lEQUt2UktxclJLZ0dSaEdzX1MxbXdqbGw2bkRWVF=
hxND0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm5ld3MvdGhlLWVzdGVlLWxhdWRlci1leG9kdXMvP=
3V0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1UaGUrQmFja3N0b3J5Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4OCUyRjI0JTJGMjQl=
MjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fY29udGVudD1UaGUrQmFja3N0b3J5Ky0rU1VCU0NSSUJFUlMrJTI4NyUyRjE=
5JTJGMjQlMjlcdTAwMjZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsX2FjdGlvblx1MDAyNnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9Y3=
VzdG9tZXIuaW9cdTAwMjZ1dG1fdGVybT1mNmM2MDYxN2RhNDJhYmQxMmEiLCJpbnRlcm5hbCI6I=
mY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImxpbmtfaWQiOjEwMDQyNTN9/152a93776e1d47a4231a2e1=
756ec271299da8ed04e011466cff88bb8eb6823f9" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-deco=
ration:none;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">The Est=C3=A9e Exodus</a></u></=
i>, to fully comprehend the familial, political, and economic dynamics.<br/=
><br/>But if you only have time for one late summer weekend read, I=E2=80=
=99d turn your attention to <i>another</i> double-barreled piece regarding =
another sort of succession. Right after Rachel filed her story on Freda, my=
 partner <b>John Ourand </b>emailed me a copy of <b>Edgar Bronfman Jr.</b>=
=E2=80=99s pitch deck to investors to acquire Paramount Global from
<i>another </i>scion, <b>Shari Redstone</b>. <br/><br/>Yes, yes, I know tha=
t the sprawling, certifiably endless Paramount auction has been an infatuat=
ion here at Puck=E2=80=94some bankers have joked, half seriously, that we s=
hould collect a deal fee on the transaction from all our perspicacious repo=
rting=E2=80=94but now John has unveiled the latest twist. Bronfman=E2=80=99=
s pitch deck not only crystallizes his strategy for the company, but also t=
he management team he=E2=80=99d deploy into Times Square to fix the busines=
s. <i><u><a href=3D"https://email.puck.news/e/c/eyJlbWFpbF9pZCI6ImRnVDJ4Z1l=
EQUt2UktxclJLZ0dSaEdzX1MxbXdqbGw2bkRWVFhxND0iLCJocmVmIjoiaHR0cHM6Ly9wdWNrLm=
5ld3MvZWRnYXItYnJvbmZtYW5zLWNsb3NpbmctcGl0Y2gtZm9yLXBhcmFtb3VudC8_dXRtX2Nhb=
XBhaWduPVRoZStCYWNrc3RvcnkrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjg4JTJGMjQlMkYyNCUyOVx1MDAy=
NnV0bV9jb250ZW50PVRoZStCYWNrc3RvcnkrLStTVUJTQ1JJQkVSUyslMjg3JTJGMTklMkYyNCU=
yOVx1MDAyNnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWxfYWN0aW9uXHUwMDI2dXRtX3NvdXJjZT1jdXN0b21lci=
5pb1x1MDAyNnV0bV90ZXJtPWY2YzYwNjE3ZGE0MmFiZDEyYSIsImludGVybmFsIjoiZjZjNjA2M=
TdkYTQyYWJkMTJhIiwibGlua19pZCI6MTAwNTc3MX0/8042391e990472a38737c4ef718eef77=
d5ae49ddc36347597fca37445f231e67" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:no=
ne;font-weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">Bronfman=E2=80=99s Closing Pitch</a></u>=
</i> eloquently builds on the previous reportage from <b>Matt Belloni</b> a=
nd <b>Bill Cohan </b>and yet crystallizes it in a new light. After all, thi=
s is one of the great sagas of our time,
and precisely what you should expect from Puck.<br/><br/>Have a great weeke=
nd,<br/>Jon<br/></td>
